  "distance": "308.052 km (191.415 miles)",
  "event_preview": "Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps measures 7.004 km (4.352 mi) and features 19 turns carved through the Ardennes forests in Stavelot, Wallonia, Belgium — the longest circuit on the Formula 1 calendar. Originally conceived in 1921 as a 14.9 km triangular road course, the track was fundamentally redesigned in 1979 into its current form, though its essential character — dramatic elevation changes, high-speed commitment and notoriously unpredictable weather — has never changed. The legendary Eau Rouge–Raidillon complex, where cars crest a blind 40-metre climb at over 300 km/h, remains one of the defining challenges in all of motorsport. The Kemmel Straight that follows is the longest on the calendar and one of the prime overtaking zones, leading into the technical Les Combes chicane. Spa's microclimate in the Ardennes is famous for producing conditions where one sector can be dry while another is under heavy rain — a factor that has influenced countless race outcomes across the circuit's century-long history. The official race lap record stands at 1:44.701, set by Sergio Pérez for Red Bull during the 2024 Belgian Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Lewis Hamilton, who clocked a 1:42.252 for Mercedes in Q3 of the 2018 weekend.",
  "tyre_compounds": "Tyre supplier Pirelli brought the C1, C3, and C4 tyre compounds.",
